article.description: Shareef Abdur-Rahim had 25 points and 10 rebounds to lead the Trail Blazers to a 90-81 victory over the Hornets.
article.headline: New Orleans loses eighth straight at home
article.linkText: Blazers finally win one on the road, beat Hornets
article.story:
NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- The Portland Trail Blazers haven't had much reason to celebrate lately. That changed for one night, thanks to the New Orleans Hornets. Shareef Abdur-Rahim had 25 points and 10 rebounds and the Trail Blazers beat the Hornets 90-81 on Sunday night. The victory snapped three losing streaks for Portland -- seven games overall, 10 in a row on the road and four straight against New Orleans. The Trail Blazers, losers of 14 of their last 15 and 20 of 22, avoided setting their longest losing streak of the season. "Losing beats you down," Abdur-Rahim said. "It feels good to win. It's good for everybody." It was the Trail Blazers' first victory on the road against a Western Conference opponent since they beat Golden State 78-75 in the season opener. It was also just the third victory for Kevin Pritchard, who took over as Portland's interim coach on March 2. "When you're losing everything gets amplified," Pritchard said. "Your problems get amplified. Maybe this will ease some of that stuff." New Orleans, which has the worst record in the Western Conference, lost its third straight overall and eighth in a row at home. "I'm going to keep evaluating," Hornets coach Byron Scott said. "I want guys that play this game with a purpose. I don't care if the season is basically over as far as playoff implications and things like that." Damon Stoudamire, who scored 84 points in Portland's two earlier losses to New Orleans, played with a bruised left shoulder and finished with 19. Ruben Patterson added 16 points and Travis Outlaw scored 13. Lee Nailon led New Orleans with 20 points in 28 minutes. P.J. Brown added 14 points, and J.R. Smith and David West each had 11. "We get up for every game, no matter what our record is and who is the team we're going up against," Nailon said. Dan Dickau, who came off the bench to score 25 and 17 points respectively in the Hornets' earlier victories over the Trail Blazers, was held to nine points. The score was tied at 25 at the end of the first quarter, but New Orleans' sloppy play in the second helped Portland take a 50-44 halftime lead. The Trail Blazers scored 11 points off 10 turnovers by the Hornets in the first half. Portland opened the third quarter with a 12-6 run, fueled by six points from Abdur-Rahim, to stretch its lead to 64-50. New Orleans made four straight free throws to cut its deficit to 70-60 at the end of the third. The Hornets used an 8-1 run, capped by West's three-point play, to cut the deficit to 71-68 with 9:58 remaining. However, they got no closer the rest of the way. New Orleans shot just 41 percent and committed 19 turnovers that led to 23 points for Portland. "I think we needed a win and they needed a win," Abdur-Rahim said. "I think in the situation we're in, not being in the playoffs and all, we all have to collectively make sure that we go out and play hard and compete to win the game and be professionals for the rest of the season and not let ourselves slip by the wayside."

Game notes
The Hornets have trailed by double figures in 52 of the 75 games this season. ... Abdur-Rahim scored two shy of his season high 27 points. ... Dickau has led or tied for the team lead in scoring 17 times this season. ... With 10 assists against the Trail Blazers, Dickau has led them in assists 31 times. ... The Hornets averaged 101.6 points in their last 10 home wins.
